To create an Adobe Bridge startup script that adds a custom menu item under the Tools tab to copy the names of selected files to the clipboard, you will need to write a JavaScript file that utilizes Bridge's Scripting API.

Here's a step-by-step guide on how to create the startup script:

1. Open a plain text editor like Notepad on Windows or TextEdit on macOS.

2. Copy and paste the following script into your editor:

```javascript
if (BridgeTalk.appName == "bridge") {
    // Create a new menu item in the Tools menu
    var menu = MenuElement.create('command', 'Copy Filenames to Clipboard', 'at the end of tools');

    menu.onSelect = function () {
        // Get the selected thumbnails
        var selectedThumbnails = app.document.getSelection();

        // Map the selected file names into an array
        var filenames = selectedThumbnails.map(function (thumbnail) {
            return thumbnail.name;
        });

        // Join the array of names into a string with line breaks
        var namesString = filenames.join("\n");

        // Copy the names to the system clipboard
        copyToClipboard(namesString);
    };

    function copyToClipboard(text) {
        if (window.clipboardData) { // For Internet Explorer
            window.clipboardData.setData("Text", text);
        } else { // For other browsers
            var clipboard = new AdobeScriptClipboard();
            clipboard.copy(text); // This may not work in all versions. In that case, a manual copy alternative should be provided
        }
    }
}
```

3. Save the script with a `.jsx` extension, for example, `CopyFilenamesToClipboard.jsx`.

4. Navigate to the Adobe Bridge startup scripts folder. The location will vary depending on the operating system and version of Bridge:
    - On Windows: `C:\Program Files\Adobe\Adobe Bridge <Version>\Startup Scripts\`
    - On macOS: `/Applications/Adobe Bridge <Version>/Startup Scripts/`

    Replace `<Version>` with your actual Adobe Bridge version number.

5. Place your `CopyFilenamesToClipboard.jsx` file inside the Startup Scripts folder.

6. If Bridge is already running, you'll need to restart it to activate the new startup script.

7. After restarting Adobe Bridge, you should now see the "Copy Filenames to Clipboard" item at the end of the Tools menu. Clicking this new menu item with files selected will copy their names to your clipboard.

Please note that access to the system clipboard may be restricted due to security reasons, and the `copyToClipboard` function may not work in all environments. If this is the case, you will need to implement a more sophisticated way to access the clipboard or use an external clipboard manipulation utility.

If the script is properly added under the tools menu but the file names are not being copied to the clipboard, the issue may be with the `copyToClipboard` function, as copying to the clipboard can be a bit tricky in the scripting environment of Adobe Bridge.

Adobe Bridge does not provide a direct API to access the clipboard, but you can use a workaround involving the use of system calls to copy text to the clipboard.

Here's a revised version of the script that uses an external command to handle copying to the clipboard, tailored for both Windows and macOS:

```javascript
if (BridgeTalk.appName == "bridge") {
    // Create a new menu item in the Tools menu
    var menu = MenuElement.create('command', 'Copy Filenames to Clipboard', 'at the end of tools');

    menu.onSelect = function () {
        // Get the selected thumbnails
        var selectedThumbnails = app.document.getSelection();
        // Map the selected file names into an array
        var filenames = selectedThumbnails.map(function (thumbnail) {
            return thumbnail.name;
        });
        // Join the array of names into a single string separated by new lines
        var namesString = filenames.join("\n");
        // Copy the names to the system clipboard
        copyToClipboard(namesString);
    };

    function copyToClipboard(text) {
        if (Folder.fs == "Windows") {
            // Use the Windows clip command
            var cmd = new File(Folder.temp + "/copyclip.cmd");
            cmd.open("w");
            cmd.writeln("@echo off");
            cmd.writeln("echo " + text.replace(/\n/g, "\r\n") + " | clip");
            cmd.close();
            cmd.execute();
            cmd.remove();
        } else {
            // Use the macOS pbcopy command
            var clipboardScript = new File(Folder.temp + "/copyclip.sh");
            clipboardScript.open("w");
            clipboardScript.writeln("#!/bin/sh");
            clipboardScript.writeln("echo " + text.quote() + " | pbcopy");
            clipboardScript.close();
            clipboardScript.execute();
            clipboardScript.remove();
        }
    }
}
```

This script will write a temporary batch file (for Windows) or shell script (for macOS) that pipes the filenames string to the `clip` or `pbcopy` command, which handles the clipboard operation on the respective operating system. It then executes this batch file or shell script and finally removes it to clean up.

After updating the script, you should place it in the Bridge `Startup Scripts` folder as you did before and restart Adobe Bridge. When you select this menu item under the Tools tab, it should now copy the file names of the selected items to the clipboard.

